x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.169, p.437 (1971)

x4freetext: .For Long Lived Products
.For Short Lived Products
The Targets were Irradiated in Air at a Distance of
4 Meters from a 60 Degree Bending Magnet and of 1 Meter
From a Thin Al Window at the End of the Vacuum System,
Thus Strongly Reducing the Secondary Neutron Flux at
The Target Position.
Short-Lived Activities (ABOUT LESS THAN 15 MINUTES
HALF-LIFE) Were Transported by Means of a Rabbit System
And not Normalized to the Monitor Reaction Given.
`Since the Authors Quote Absolute Cross Sections
It can be Assumed That the Measured Relative Cross
Sections have Been Normalized to One of the Long-Lived
Activities (COMMENT BY THE COMPILER OF KACHAPAG).`

x4codes.hlp: Space Radiation Effects Lab., Newport News, VA, United States of America

x4freetext: Foils of Natural Cu, Ni, Fe and Al with Thicknesses
Ranging from 50 to 1000 Mg/Cm**2 and Purities Ranging
From 99.90% For Fe to 99.999% For the Other Foils were
Irradiated Simultaneously.
To Prevent Contamination from Recoil Nuclei the Foils
Were Separated by 18 Mg/Cm**2 Plastic.   The Total
Package was Thin Enough That There were No Measurable
Effects from Secondary Particles.
Short-Lived Activities with Half-Lives Less Than About
15 Minutes were Produced in Cylindrical Targets of
7 mm Diameter and 15 mm Length Transported by a Fast
Rabbit System. It is not Explicitly Quoted in the
Publication Which of the Measured Activities were
Obtained from this Kind of Target. The Iron Rabbits
Showed a Higher Degree of Impurities Than the Other
Rabbits and the Target Foils Resulting in a Higher
Manganese Concentration in the Spallation Products
Relative to the Produced Scandium.
A Cross Section of 10.8 Mb was Used

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Annual Review of Nuclear and Part.Sci., Vol.9, p.159 (1959)

x4freetext: Probably One of the Numerous References Cited in this
Review Article Contains the Numerical Value Used in
The Present Paper.
The Errors Given Include Uncertainties and
Reproducibilities of the Gamma-Ray Intensities
Determined. For Stronger Transitions the Absolute
Intensity was Accurate to 5%. Included are
Also Uncertainties of the Branching Ratios and
Half-Lives. Not Included is the Error in the Monitor
Cross Section.
The Results are Compared to Calculated Cross Sections
According to the Formula of K.F.Chackett Et Al., Nucl.
